Coronavirus: stay up to date
Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in North Macedonia. See information on measures introduced in North Macedonia to limit the spread of the virus. Find out how to return to the UK from North Macedonia.
See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on international travel.
Sign up for email alerts for North Macedonia travel advice.
The Government of the Republic of North Macedonia has introduced a curfew in force from 9pm until 5am.
On 24 March the Government of the Republic of North Macedonia introduced a new measure against the outbreak of coronavirus, to restrict the movement of people under 18 and people over 67. People under 18 will be able to go outside only between 12pm and 9pm and people over 67 between 5am and 11am.
On 23 March the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) updated its global travel advice to recommend that if you live in the UK and are currently travelling abroad, you are strongly advised to return now, where and while there are still commercial routes available. There are currently no commercial routes available in North Macedonia. For full information see Coronavirus and Return to the UK
On 14 February 2019, the UK government was informed that the Republic of Macedonia was henceforth known as the Republic of North Macedonia.
Most visits to North Macedonia are trouble-free. Occasional acts of criminal violence occur, although foreigners are not generally targeted.
Take particular care if you travel to northern areas of the country near the border with Kosovo. See Crime and Local travel
Political rallies and demonstrations could occur. See Political situation
Terrorists are likely to try to carry out attacks in North Macedonia. See Terrorism
Mosquito-borne diseases, including West Nile virus are present. See Health
Earthquakes occasionally occur. See Natural disasters
